<li>    For more information, see Adam D. Thierer, "Who Will Mind the Children?  The Regulation of Children's Programming in the Information Age," in <I>Speaking Freely: The Public Interest in Unfettered Speech</I> (Washington, D.C.: The Media Institute, 1995), pp. 47-66.<P>
<li>    United States Constitution, Amendment 1.<p>
<li>    Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, p. 18.<p>
<li>    For a more detailed discussion of this dual system of regulation, see <I>Print and Electronic Media: The Case for First Amendment Parity</I>, Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation, 98th Congress, 1st Session Committee Print, May 3, 1983; Jonathan W. Emord, <I>Freedom, Technology, and the First Amendment</I> (San Francisco, Cal: Pacific Research Institute, 1991); Matthew L. Spitzer, "The Constitutionality of Licensing Broadcasters," <I>New York University Law Review</I> Vol. 64 (1989), p. 990; John Thorne, Peter W. Huber, and Michael K. Kellogg, "Free Speech," in <I>Federal Broadband Law</I> (Little, Brown & Co., forthcoming); Krattenmaker and Powe, "Broadcasting Versus Print," in <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 203-236; Harry Kalven, Jr., "Broadcasting, Public Policy and the First Amendment," <I>The Journal of Law and Economics</I>, Vol. 10 (October 1967), pp. 15-49.<p>
<li>    Timothy Dyk, "Full First Amendment Freedom for Broadcasters: The Industry as Eliza on the Ice and Congress as the Friendly Overseer," <I>Yale Journal of Regulation</I> Vol. 5 (1988), pp. 299, 308.<p>
<li>    See <I>Miami Herald Publishing Company v. Tornillo</I>, 418 U.S. 241 (1974); <I>Pacific Gas & Electric Company v. Public Utilities Commission</I>, 475 U.S. 1 (1986); <I>Near v. Minnesota</I>, 283 U.S. 697 (1931).<p>
<li>    Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, p. 235.<p>
<li>    See generally Robert Corn-Revere, "Who Speaks for the First Amendment: Why the FCC Should Look Before It Leaps on Children's TV," <I>Broadcasting & Cable</I>, June 27, 1994, p. 19; Robert Corn-Revere, "Television Violence and the Limits of Voluntarism," <I>Yale Journal of Regulation</I>, Vol. 12, No. 1 (Winter 1995), p. 205.<p>
<li>    Bruce Fein, "First Class First Amendment Rights for Broadcasters," <I>Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy</I>, Vol. 10, No. 1 (Winter 1987), p. 84.<p>
