<li>    See Fred H. Cate, "The First Amendment and the National Information Infrastructure," <I>Wake Forest Law Review</I>, Vol. 30, No. 1 (Spring 1995), pp. 37-40; Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 204-205.<p>
<li>    While granting property rights may seem like nothing more than a natural extension of providing full flexibility in use, an important difference exists. Full flexibility could be granted to spectrum users while they continue to lease their allocation from the federal government. While this system would be vastly more efficient than the current system, the federal government would still own the resource and would merely be granting licenses for a given period. Therefore, bureaucratic meddling could remain a serious problem, especially with regard to content regulation.<p>
<li>    The NTIA, which sits in the Department of Commerce, manages all federal government spectrum, such as that used for air traffic control, law enforcement, and especially military concerns.<p>
<li>    See generally, <I>The Telecom Revolution: An American Opportunity</I>, p. 70-79.
</ol><p>
